This PR partially addresses the engine updates outlined in #4767 which are required to natively support ES Modules. This is just a draft with the aim to review the proposed API. All comments are welcome.

**New ESM format**

```javascript
export const attributes = {
    aNumber: { name: 'String', default: 10, min: 0, max: 199 }
}

class MyModule {
    // called once
    constructor(entity, app, { aNumber }){}

    // lifecycle hooks (TBD)
    update(dt, { aNumber }){}
    destroy(){}
}

export default MyModule
```

**Reference Project**
https://playcanvas.com/editor/scene/1866257 (use ?local_engine) to test against this PR

Few points:
- Does not extend a base class. It's not required and allows devs to use their own super class. 
- attributes are isolated from class definition as they're only used by the editor and can therefore be shaken out at runtime.
- Needs to support hot module replacement, but I personally find the `swap` method confusing and can actually be simplified and solved with destroy and constructor which requires less cognitive overhead. This seems to be [echoed by the community](https://discord.com/channels/408617316415307776/905402009849577474/1164194791714725898)
- It might be easier to  to directly add attribute values on the class instance as opposed to passing in lifecycle hooks
- This currently limits the module to export only 1 class per module, but I feel this is a constraint that leads to a cleaner API
- There's definitely things I've overlooked

I confirm I have read the [contributing guidelines](https://github.com/playcanvas/engine/blob/master/.github/CONTRIBUTING.md) and signed the [Contributor License Agreement](https://docs.google.com/a/playcanvas.com/forms/d/1Ih69zQfJG-QDLIEpHr6CsaAs6fPORNOVnMv5nuo0cjk/viewform).

